{"title":"The bikes of the 2023 Sea Otter Classic","link":"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/05/the-bikes-of-the-2023-sea-otter-classic/","date":1683027050000,"content":"<figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7865.jpg?width=1200\" alt=\"The bikes of the 2023 Sea Otter Classic\" /></figure><figure></figure>\n<figure>There were a lot of bikes at the 2023 Sea Otter Classic, and while MTB always seems to be the main focus, there were a lot of impressive road and gravel options. It is hard to pick a favorite, but here is a handful that stood out during our four days of booth hopping.</figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/NO.22_1-1340x894.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"894\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/NO.22_1-scaled.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/NO.22_1-scaled.jpg?width=190 190w\" /></figure>\n<figure>\n<figure><figcaption><span>With all of the beautiful bikes at Sea Otter, this No22 Great Divide might have been the showstopper. To be honest, all the bikes in the booth were impressive, and I love the integration of modern techniques like 3D-printed components. </span></figcaption></figure>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/A446B74B-DBF3-4BE6-971C-944CCA2A524B-2172-0000028581B09B11-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/A446B74B-DBF3-4BE6-971C-944CCA2A524B-2172-0000028581B09B11.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/A446B74B-DBF3-4BE6-971C-944CCA2A524B-2172-0000028581B09B11.jpg?width=190 190w\" /></p><figcaption><span>This Miami Blazers Canyon Aeroad that is on display at SRAM was stopping everyone. The new race team is riding in style, that is for sure.</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/4B3C8CBC-4B6F-4DB0-AA15-FE274C581FB4-2172-00000285875DF645-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/4B3C8CBC-4B6F-4DB0-AA15-FE274C581FB4-2172-00000285875DF645.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/4B3C8CBC-4B6F-4DB0-AA15-FE274C581FB4-2172-00000285875DF645.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>The Pinarello X1 Disc is a solid offering with Shimano 105 drivetrain and endurance geo. At $3700, it’s a great price for such a striking bike.</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/A0A8BB8A-0ED1-4820-A886-534B06FF5376-2172-000002858A54902F.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1184\" height=\"1776\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/A0A8BB8A-0ED1-4820-A886-534B06FF5376-2172-000002858A54902F.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/A0A8BB8A-0ED1-4820-A886-534B06FF5376-2172-000002858A54902F.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span><span>The Filante SLR is Wilier’s aero road race offering. The gold paint is what really sets this bike apart.<br />\n</span></span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Willier-Rave-SLR-complete-gravel-bike.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Willier-Rave-SLR-complete-gravel-bike\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Willier-Rave-SLR-complete-gravel-bike.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Willier-Rave-SLR-complete-gravel-bike.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Wilier also brought their Rave SLR gravel bike. Ivar Slik won on this bike, and I’m sure the Italian manufacturer will point to this bike as the reason why. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Willier-Rave-SLR-toptube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Willier-Rave-SLR-toptube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Willier-Rave-SLR-toptube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Willier-Rave-SLR-toptube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>I’m not normally a fan of camo paint in any application, but I can make an exception for this one. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><figcaption>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-side.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-side\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-side.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-side.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Diamondback brought their new Haanjo gravel bike. This one was custom-painted by Tec-Gnar out of Price, Utah with a paint scheme straight out of the 1990s. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-fork.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-fork\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-fork.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-fork.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Splatter paint and disc brakes. I’m happy to see it. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-headtube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-headtube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-headtube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-headtube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>The old-school Diamondback logos mesh neatly with the splatter paint and paint-matched Rockshox Rudy suspension fork. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-seattube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-seattube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-seattube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Diamondback-Haanjo-gravel-bike-green-custom-paint-seattube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>I can’t get enough of that ’90s logo. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-complete.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-complete\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-complete.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-complete.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Felt showed off their new Breed Carbon gravel bike in myriad builds. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-downtube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-downtube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-downtube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-downtube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>The bike looks well-finished overall. The top tube features a bag mount, while the downtube has two different bottle mounts. There’s also a bottle mount near the bottom bracket and one mount on the seattube. Hydration matters, folks! (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n</figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-bottom-bracket.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-bottom-bracket\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-bottom-bracket.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-bottom-bracket.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>The Breed features plenty of frame protection, including a bottom bracket rubber protector and a fully-encased rubber chainstay protector. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-handlebars.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-handlebars\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-handlebars.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Felt-Breed-Carbon-gravel-bike-yellow-handlebars.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>No internal cable routing to be found here! Stay tuned as we’ve requested a Breed Carbon for review. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-with-polish.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-with-polish\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-with-polish.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-with-polish.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>This was the first time I saw the 50th Anniversary Ritchey Outback frame in the flesh, and it looks great. The polished alloy and leather touch points add some old-school appeal. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><figcaption>\n<figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-handebar.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-handebar\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-handebar.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-handebar.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Leather tape, gum brake lever hoods, bar-end shifting, and polished components starkly contrast most of the other bikes at Sea Otter. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n</figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-seatpost.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-seatpost\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-seatpost.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Ritchey-Outback-gravel-bike-in-blue-seatpost.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span><span>The Outback 50th Anniversary frame received old-school font. The half-moon blue fade works nicely with the steel frame’s fastback seatstays. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></span> </figcaption></figure>\n</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7571-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7571.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7571.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Vitus was showing off their new Venon Evo. It is an all-road bike that is offered in a handful of gravel builds as well as road-oriented builds too. </span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7569-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7569.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7569.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span><span>The Venon Evo gravel builds are all 1x, while the road builds are 2x.</span></span> </figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7875-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7875.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7875.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>The Vielo + Classified R+1 is a partnership to make the ultimate modern road bike. Vielo’s vision of engineering frames optimized to the benefits of a single chainring pairs perfectly with the Classified’s virtual front mech. Best of all, Vielo has also adapted a dropper post, because why not?</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7883-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7883.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7883.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>The R+1 now has all the benefits of 1x, with the increased gearing range from Classified’s powershift technology.<br />\n</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7865-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7865.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7865.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Vielo was showing off the new WTB collab. The Vielo + WTB V+1 is a modern off-road racer with an eye on the past. Inspired by the Repack gang of the early ’80s, each frame is hand-painted to produce a do-it-yourself vibe.</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7869-1340x2010.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"2010\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7869.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7869.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Colorful and loud, this V+1 will never be missed.<br />\n</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7584-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7584.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7584.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>One of the most displayed bikes this year was the Ritte Esprit. I got to take a quick Sunday morning spin on one, and it didn’t disappoint, nor did the 17-mile drive scenery. </span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7595-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7595.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7595.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span><span>The Ritte Esprit can be built with these Ritte integrated one-piece cockpit or a traditional cockpit. The frame features a T47 threaded bottom bracket, 27.2mm seatpost compatibility, and tire clearance for up to 35mm.</span></span> </figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7620-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7620.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7620.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Haley Cycles is all about custom titanium. The Haley Race Disc is a road race geometry, oversized Ti tubeset with an Enve carbon fork. It has internal routing, flat-mount disc brakes, and room for 32mm tires.</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7621-1340x2010.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"2010\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7621.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7621.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span><span>This particular build also got the Absoluteblack Hollowcage upgrade.</span></span> </figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7759-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7759.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7759.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>It looks like the Rotor team was out doing some top-secret testing. I wonder what they are working on next? Maybe I’ll get to see something road-specific at Eurobike. </span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7767-1340x893.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7767.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/SO-23-7767.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>The best ride award at the show goes to this crew.</span></figcaption></figure>","author":"Troy Templin","siteTitle":"CyclingTips","siteHash":"30feca30fb3902119bf2da6559e7337232527b61c9abe0a00f5d7543c6aa6c84","entryHash":"1e6183f62afdda971050209bd50eb1773ce6ea90e0b18baaff4caca9bbf5f97d","category":"Cycling"}